04476nam a22005535i 9780674919907DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749199077 a10.4159/97806749199072doi  a(DE-B1597)501440  a(OCoLC)1022945329  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aE184.C5bL564 2018eb 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a305.895/10732231 aLew-Williams, Beth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Chinese Must Go :bViolence, Exclusion, and the Making of the Alien in America /cBeth Lew-Williams. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b15 halftones, 6 maps, 1 chart, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Violence of Exclusion -- tPART 1. Restriction -- tThe Chinese Question -- tExperiments in Restriction -- tPart 2. Violence -- tThe Banished -- tThe People -- tThe Loyal -- tPart 3. Exclusion -- tThe Exclusion Consensus -- tAfterlives Under Exclusion -- tEpilogue. The Modern American Alien -- tAppendix A -- tAppendix B -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe American West erupted in anti-Chinese violence in 1885. Following the massacre of Chinese miners in Wyoming Territory, communities throughout California and the Pacific Northwest harassed, assaulted, and expelled thousands of Chinese immigrants. Beth Lew-Williams shows how American immigration policies incited this violence and how the violence, in turn, provoked new exclusionary policies. Ultimately, Lew-Williams argues, Chinese expulsion and exclusion produced the concept of the “alien” in modern America. The Chinese Must Go begins in the 1850s, before federal border control established strict divisions between citizens and aliens. Across decades of felling trees and laying tracks in the American West, Chinese workers faced escalating racial conflict and unrest. In response, Congress passed the Chinese Restriction Act of 1882 and made its first attempt to bar immigrants based on race and class. When this unprecedented experiment in federal border control failed to slow Chinese migration, vigilantes attempted to take the matter into their own hands. Fearing the spread of mob violence, U.S. policymakers redoubled their efforts to keep the Chinese out, overhauling U.S. immigration law and transforming diplomatic relations with China. By locating the origins of the modern American alien in this violent era, Lew-Williams recasts the significance of Chinese exclusion in U.S. history. As The Chinese Must Go makes clear, anti-Chinese law and violence continues to have consequences for today’s immigrants. The present resurgence of xenophobia builds mightily upon past fears of the “heathen Chinaman.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAlienszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aBorder securityzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aChinesexViolence againstzUnited States. 0aChinesezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aRace discriminationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067491990740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674919907423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674919907.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles